<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05176o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05176o">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05176o"> 176(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Mrs Kate Lee a waitress to / get folk airs from carters</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The first secretary of the Folk Song Society, <mark>Mrs. Kate Lee</mark>, was emboldened to attempt an even more desperate enterprise. <mark>To get hold of some folk songs</mark> which she knew were reserved for the ears of the <mark>frequenters of a country inn</mark> in The Broads, she obtained admittance <mark>as a waitress</mark> at the ordinary table and when the diners had settled down to beer, tobacco, and song, she got those precious folk songs into her head, and kept them there for the benefit of the society</mark>. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Folk Song] 179</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
